observations.recommendation:
We recommended that management instruct:
the Municipal Accountant to exclude as Deposits in Transit, those after           cut-off collections on the last working day of the month which were deposited on the succeeding month;
the Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of reporting in the Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD) those deposits which have deposit slips validated on the succeeding month in order;
the Municipal Treasurer to explain the absence of machine validation on deposit slips of collections considered as Deposits in Transit and use of Cash Deposit Slips for the deposit of checks;
the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the discrepancy of ₱57,888.11 on the amount of Outstanding Checks per BRS and List of Outstanding Checks.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Identify those projects not yet completed as of December 31, 2020 and recognize the appropriate CIP accounts which correspond to on-going projects;

Compute for the overstated amount of Depreciated Expense using the date of actual completion per Certificate of Completion as the reckoning date;

Refrain from directly recording PPE accounts upon payment of progress billings to contractors and recognize corresponding PPE accounts only upon completion of projects, followed by the recognition of depreciation expense in order to fairly present the PPE accounts and Net Income in the financial statements.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant prioritize the reconstruction of the subsidiary ledgers for all Construction in Progress accounts so as to provide accurate supporting data for the corresponding general ledger account balances;

Municipal Engineer assist the Municipal Accountant by providing copies of Program of Works, Statement of Work Accomplished, Certificates of Completion and Turn-over of all infrastructure projects in the current and prior years, when needed, so as to supply data required in the reconstruction of the CIP account SLs;

Municipal Accountant conduct a periodic reconciliation of inventory of completed projects with the records of the Municipal Engineer so as to promptly recognize completed projects and drop the corresponding amount in the related CIP accounts;

(d) Management extend assistance to the Municipal Accounting Office, such as assignment of additional personnel to the Accounting Office, to enable them meet all the required financial reports and documents, pursuant to the requirements of COA Circular No.2010-001.

We recommended that management:

(a) Control disbursements based on available appropriation and not on available cash balances per bank;

(b) Stop using cash reserves for trust liabilities for payment of other expenditures;

(c) Use Trust Fund only for specific expenditures for which it was created or received;

(d) Prioritize payment of outstanding and statutory obligations to avoid penalties and surcharges;

(e) Institute measures to properly monitor Cash in Bank balances.

We recommended that:

the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant submit pertinent documents to the Audit Team to prove the validity of the inclusion of reconciling items added to the bank balance per book and bank to facilitate the expeditious review of BRS and establish reliability of the reported Cash in Bank balance;

the Municipal Accountant meticulously review every RCD submitted by the Municipal Treasurer and record only those deposits duly supported with validated deposit slips as of RCD date, including those other book reconciling items which are added to the bank balance per book;

the Municipal Treasurer discontinue the afore-cited practice and fairly report collections and deposits in the RCD by including only those deposits duly supported with validated deposit slips as of RCD date.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

direct the Inventory Committee to properly plan ahead and determine the schedule for physical count per department in order to prioritize and fully realize the conduct of a complete physical count of inventories and PPEs of the LGU;

require the Inventory Committee to prepare the RPCPPE and RPCI and submit copies thereof to the Municipal Accountant, immediately after the conduct of physical count, for reconciliation with accounting records, and furnish similar copy thereof to the audit team order to verify compliance with Section 124 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs;

instruct the General Services Officer (GSO) to trace the Property Acknowledgment Receipts (PAR) issued to accountable officers/employees, in order to pinpoint property accountability, should the result of the physical count be less than that of the accounting records, due to missing or unserviceable PPE items and inventories. 

direct the Inventory Committee and Municipal Accountant to submit copies of proof of reconciliation between GSO and accounting records to the audit team, for validation purposes, in order to fully and properly document adjustments to be taken up by the Municipal Accountant in the LGU books, if warranted.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
a.	ensure compliance with the provisions pertaining to the receipts and distributions of the donations in-kind received by the City so that they will be properly accounted for;
b.	direct the City Social Welfare and Development Officer to submit the Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances within ten working days after the end of each quarter as prescribed in the circular.

